TY  - JOUR
T1  - Is the Simultaneous Verbal Protocol a Viable Method for Studying Managerial Problem Solving and Decision Making?
AU  - Schweiger, David M.
Y1  - 1983/03/01
PY  - 1983
DA  - 1983/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256146
DO  - 10.5465/256146
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 185
EP  - 192
VL  - 26
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The article assesses the impact of the simultaneous verbal protocol on problem solving and decision making performance for a complex managerial task. The author believes there has been an increasing focus by management and decision researchers in examining managerial problem solving and decision making, but it is still not well known. Fourty graduate business students engaged in a computer-simulation management game that required they make 17 decisions per period. The study entailed ten decision periods. Performance was measured by operating profit, return on assets, and market share. The study found little difference between those that used simultaneous verbal protocols and those that did not.
AB  - The article assesses the impact of the simultaneous verbal protocol on problem solving and decision making performance for a complex managerial task. The author believes there has been an increasing focus by management and decision researchers in examining managerial problem solving and decision making, but it is still not well known. Fourty graduate business students engaged in a computer-simulation management game that required they make 17 decisions per period. The study entailed ten decision periods. Performance was measured by operating profit, return on assets, and market share. The study found little difference between those that used simultaneous verbal protocols and those that did not.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/256146
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/256146
Y2  - 2026/04/24
