TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Effects of Representatives' Power within their own Organizations on the outcome of a Negotiation
AU  - Jackson, Conrad N.
AU  - King, Donald C.
Y1  - 1983/03/01
PY  - 1983
DA  - 1983/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256145
DO  - 10.5465/256145
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 178
EP  - 184
VL  - 26
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The article examines the impact of representatives' power within their own organization on the outcome of a negotiation and the dynamics of interorganizational relationships. The authors begin by discussing various studies that have been done and explains the focus of each. They believe that a high-power boundary-spanning person (BSP) (a person who links one organization to another) will complete negotiations in less time with fewer deadlocks, get more resources exchanged, and achieve greater productivity and greater satisfaction. To test this theory, they used 120 undergraduate students. They found that negotiation time was affected by interorganizational power of BSPs.
AB  - The article examines the impact of representatives' power within their own organization on the outcome of a negotiation and the dynamics of interorganizational relationships. The authors begin by discussing various studies that have been done and explains the focus of each. They believe that a high-power boundary-spanning person (BSP) (a person who links one organization to another) will complete negotiations in less time with fewer deadlocks, get more resources exchanged, and achieve greater productivity and greater satisfaction. To test this theory, they used 120 undergraduate students. They found that negotiation time was affected by interorganizational power of BSPs.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/256145
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/256145
Y2  - 2026/04/24
